const title = "Where Should You Fish Near Missoula?";
---

<Layout title={title}>
  <h1>{title}</h1>

  <p>
    With this many rivers and lakes nearby, the real question usually
    isn't "is the fishing good here" — it's "which water actually fits
    what I want to do." Here's a simple way to think about it, based
    on what you're after.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>If you want the classic Montana fly fishing experience:</strong> Head to the Blackfoot River. It's the river from
    <em>A River Runs Through It</em>, and it's still one of the best
    places anywhere to learn fly fishing with a guide. If you've only
    got time for one river near Missoula, this is a strong pick.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>If you want a relaxed day, wading or floating:</strong> The Bitterroot and the Clark Fork are both excellent, approachable
    rivers close to town — good for a laid-back day on the water,
    whether you're new to fishing or just want an easy outing.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>If you want a serious trout stream with a real reputation:</strong> Rock Creek is one of Montana's official Blue Ribbon trout streams,
    known for its healthy population of wild trout. It's a smaller
    stream than the Blackfoot or Bitterroot, and it draws anglers who
    take their fishing seriously.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>If you want a shot at something big:</strong> Flathead Lake is enormous, and the lake trout in it can be
    enormous too — the state record caught there weighed over 42
    pounds. It also has hefty mountain whitefish and year-round
    trolling charters, including trips through the winter.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>If you want variety in a single trip:</strong> Salmon Lake and Seeley Lake both mix strong trout fishing with
    hard-fighting northern pike, so you can switch things up without
    switching lakes.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>If you want to fish through the winter:</strong> Flathead Lake runs charters nearly year-round, and Georgetown Lake
    is a solid pick for guided ice fishing. Salmon Lake and Seeley
    Lake are also popular ice fishing spots — Seeley Lake even holds
    an annual "Pike On Ice" tournament — though most anglers there
    fish on their own rather than with a guide.
  </p>

 <p>
    However you like to fish, there's a water near Missoula built for
    it. From here, take a look at how to <a href="/outdoors/fishing/how-to-pick-a-guide/">pick the right guide</a> for your
